  PARAGRAPH@1375..1780 {
    TEXT_LINE: "The only public method of a ``Flag`` object is :meth:`parse`, but it is"@1375..1446
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1446..1447
    TEXT_LINE: "typically only called by a :class:`~absl.flags.FlagValues` object.  The"@1447..1518
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1518..1519
    TEXT_LINE: ":meth:`parse` method is a thin wrapper around the"@1519..1568
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1568..1569
    TEXT_LINE: ":meth:`ArgumentParser.parse()<absl.flags.ArgumentParser.parse>` method.  The"@1569..1645
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1645..1646
    TEXT_LINE: "parsed value is saved in ``.value``, and the ``.present`` attribute is"@1646..1716
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1716..1717
    TEXT_LINE: "updated.  If this flag was already present, an Error is raised."@1717..1780
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@1780..1781
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1781..1782
  PARAGRAPH@1782..2239 {
    TEXT_LINE: ":meth:`parse` is also called during ``__init__`` to parse the default value"@1782..1857
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1857..1858
    TEXT_LINE: "and initialize the ``.value`` attribute.  This enables other python modules to"@1858..1936
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1936..1937
    TEXT_LINE: "safely use flags even if the ``__main__`` module neglects to parse the"@1937..2007
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2007..2008
    TEXT_LINE: "command line arguments.  The ``.present`` attribute is cleared after"@2008..2076
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2076..2077
    TEXT_LINE: "``__init__`` parsing.  If the default value is set to ``None``, then the"@2077..2149
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2149..2150
    TEXT_LINE: "``__init__`` parsing step is skipped and the ``.value`` attribute is"@2150..2218
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2218..2219
    TEXT_LINE: "initialized to None."@2219..2239
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@2239..2240
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2240..2241
  PARAGRAPH@2241..2373 {
    TEXT_LINE: "Note: The default value is also presented to the user in the help"@2241..2306
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2306..2307
    TEXT_LINE: "string, so it is important that it be a legal value for this flag."@2307..2373
  }
}
=== EMIT ===
Information about a command-line flag.

Attributes:
    name: the name for this flag
    default: the default value for this flag
    default_unparsed: the unparsed default value for this flag.
    default_as_str: default value as repr'd string, e.g., "'true'" (or None)
    value: the most recent parsed value of this flag set by :meth:`parse`
    help: a help string or None if no help is available
    short_name: the single letter alias for this flag (or None)
    boolean: if 'true', this flag does not accept arguments
    present: true if this flag was parsed from command line flags
    parser: an :class:`~absl.flags.ArgumentParser` object
    serializer: an ArgumentSerializer object
    allow_override: the flag may be redefined without raising an error, and
        newly defined flag overrides the old one.
    allow_override_cpp: use the flag from C++ if available the flag definition
        is replaced by the C++ flag after init
    allow_hide_cpp: use the Python flag despite having a C++ flag with the same
        name (ignore the C++ flag)
    using_default_value: the flag value has not been set by user
    allow_overwrite: the flag may be parsed more than once without raising an
        error, the last set value will be used
    allow_using_method_names: whether this flag can be defined even if it has a
        name that conflicts with a FlagValues method.
    validators: list of the flag validators.
